        {
          "content": "{\n  \"files\": [\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"expressjs/express\",\n      \"path\": \"lib/request.js\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"expressjs/express\",\n      \"path\": \"test/req.host.js\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"expressjs/express\",\n      \"path\": \"History.md\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"text\": \"The deprecated `req.host` property is referenced in three key files within the Express.js repository:\\n\\n1. **lib/request.js (lines 418-431)**: This file contains the definition of the `host` getter property using the `defineGetter` utility function. The getter returns the parsed Host header field (including port if present) or X-Forwarded-Host when trust proxy is configured.\\n\\n2. **test/req.host.js**: Comprehensive test suite that validates the `req.host` property behavior across various scenarios including basic host parsing, IPv6 support, X-Forwarded-Host handling with trust proxy settings, and edge cases.\\n\\n3. **History.md**: The changelog contains multiple references to `req.host`:\\n   - Line 1526: The deprecation notice stating \\\"deprecate `req.host` -- use `req.hostname` instead\\\" (introduced in version 4.5.0 on 2014-07-04)\\n   - Line 1524: Documentation that \\\"add `req.hostname` -- correct name for what `req.host` returns\\\"\\n   - Additional entries documenting bug fixes and improvements to `req.host` functionality over various versions\\n\\nEach reference has been verified to use `req.host` as the standalone deprecated property (not as part of `req.hostname`). The deprecated property returns the full host including port, while the recommended replacement `req.hostname` returns only the hostname portion without the port number.\"\n}\n",
